1
00:01:36,295 --> 00:01:38,596
[Sighs] so...

2
00:01:38,664 --> 00:01:42,600
What do you think of
my latest masterpiece, Eliot?

3
00:01:42,668 --> 00:01:45,369
I know it isn't
one of my best.

4
00:01:45,437 --> 00:01:48,606
But it does remind me of
how pretty it was back here.

5
00:01:48,674 --> 00:01:51,976
Oh, things are fine.

6
00:01:52,044 --> 00:01:55,646
But I do miss you, Eliot.

7
00:01:57,416 --> 00:01:58,983
[Elevator dings]

8
00:02:00,485 --> 00:02:01,686
Good morning.

9
00:02:01,754 --> 00:02:04,288
Mr. Eason, you're late.
Here's your mail.

10
00:02:04,356 --> 00:02:05,523
Any calls?

11
00:02:05,591 --> 00:02:06,991
Your mother... Twice.

12
00:02:07,059 --> 00:02:08,459
Uh, Mr. Weller again.
He wasn't too thrilled

13
00:02:08,527 --> 00:02:09,961
About the fact that
you never called him back.

14
00:02:10,029 --> 00:02:11,129
Anything else?

15
00:02:11,197 --> 00:02:13,131
And Mr. Backis
is waiting for you.

16
00:02:15,835 --> 00:02:17,568
Richard, I know
that our bank

17
00:02:17,636 --> 00:02:19,237
Has been doing business
with your father

18
00:02:19,304 --> 00:02:21,639
And his company
for 50 years.

19
00:02:21,707 --> 00:02:23,507
But we're, um...

20
00:02:23,575 --> 00:02:25,910
Concerned about the
scope of this project.

21
00:02:25,978 --> 00:02:29,614
Everything is going
according to plan so far.

22
00:02:29,649 --> 00:02:34,018
Well, Richard, the board
approved the project

23
00:02:34,086 --> 00:02:35,787
With your father
at the helm.

24
00:02:35,854 --> 00:02:37,354
Since his passing,

25
00:02:37,456 --> 00:02:38,490
There has been
the question of...

26
00:02:38,557 --> 00:02:40,091
Whether I'm up
to the task.

27
00:02:40,158 --> 00:02:41,893
Your father had
decades of experience,

28
00:02:41,928 --> 00:02:44,595
And that experience is
what got this project
off the ground.

29
00:02:44,663 --> 00:02:46,597
Since my father died,
we're on schedule

30
00:02:46,665 --> 00:02:48,399
To break ground in
three weeks with no delays.

31
00:02:48,467 --> 00:02:50,634
<i>[Intercom buzzes]</i>
<i>woman: Mr. Eason?</i>

32
00:02:50,702 --> 00:02:52,937
<i>It's your mother, Richard.</i>

33
00:02:53,005 --> 00:02:54,472
Well, have her
call me back.

34
00:02:54,539 --> 00:02:55,873
<i>Honey, this is the third</i>
<i>time she's called.</i>

35
00:02:55,941 --> 00:02:57,308
<i>She says that</i>
<i>it's important.</i>

36
00:02:57,376 --> 00:02:58,944
<i>I think you should</i>
<i>take the call.</i>

37
00:02:59,011 --> 00:03:01,446
Ok, put her through.
This will just take
a second.

38
00:03:01,514 --> 00:03:03,681
Mom, I'm really busy.
<i>I need a favor.</i>

39
00:03:03,749 --> 00:03:05,783
This new easel
isn't working for me,

40
00:03:05,851 --> 00:03:08,353
And my old one's
up in the garage attic.

41
00:03:08,420 --> 00:03:09,687
I can't right now.

42
00:03:09,755 --> 00:03:11,156
I'm in the middle of
a very important meeting.

43
00:03:11,223 --> 00:03:13,491
Ok, I'll just
go get it myself.

44
00:03:13,559 --> 00:03:14,992
<i>But if I fall...</i>

45
00:03:15,061 --> 00:03:16,661
If I break my hip--

46
00:03:16,662 --> 00:03:18,929
Mom, I'm gonna have
to call you back.
<i>Fine.</i>

47
00:03:18,965 --> 00:03:21,366
And don't climb
up that ladder.

48
00:03:21,434 --> 00:03:22,733
Bye.

49
00:03:26,739 --> 00:03:30,842
%% Find that someone special %%

50
00:03:30,909 --> 00:03:35,680
%% give him love,
make him your own %%

51
00:03:35,747 --> 00:03:37,515
Hmm.

52
00:03:43,489 --> 00:03:46,324
[Musical cell phone ring]

53
00:03:49,528 --> 00:03:50,728
Hello?

54
00:03:50,796 --> 00:03:52,930
Ella bear? It's grandma.

55
00:03:52,999 --> 00:03:54,565
Hi, grandma, how are you?

56
00:03:54,633 --> 00:03:56,801
You won't believe
what your father did.

57
00:03:56,869 --> 00:03:58,436
<i>My guess is it's more of</i>
<i>what he didn't do.</i>

58
00:03:58,504 --> 00:04:00,705
<i>I can't paint</i>
<i>with this new easel,</i>

59
00:04:00,773 --> 00:04:02,373
The one your father
bought me.

60
00:04:02,441 --> 00:04:05,809
And my old one is way up
in the garage attic,

61
00:04:05,877 --> 00:04:07,845
And he says he's
too busy to come get it

62
00:04:07,913 --> 00:04:09,414
For his own mother.

63
00:04:09,481 --> 00:04:11,715
Yeah, grandma, I don't know
what you want me to do.

64
00:04:11,783 --> 00:04:13,551
It'd take me a couple
of hours to get there.

65
00:04:13,618 --> 00:04:15,819
Damn easel!

66
00:04:20,159 --> 00:04:22,393
I never expected to be
a struggling artist

67
00:04:22,461 --> 00:04:23,828
At my age.

68
00:04:23,896 --> 00:04:25,296
[Laughs]

69
00:04:26,932 --> 00:04:28,532
That was a joke.

70
00:04:30,969 --> 00:04:32,136
What's the matter?

71
00:04:32,204 --> 00:04:33,738
Are you sure
everything's ok?

72
00:04:33,806 --> 00:04:35,039
Yeah.

73
00:04:35,107 --> 00:04:36,474
How are your classes?

74
00:04:36,542 --> 00:04:38,410
They're ok.

75
00:04:38,477 --> 00:04:39,911
You're doing well?

76
00:04:39,945 --> 00:04:41,612
Yeah, my grades are fine.

77
00:04:41,680 --> 00:04:43,781
Are you still
writing songs down

78
00:04:43,849 --> 00:04:45,116
In that book of yours?

79
00:04:45,184 --> 00:04:46,751
Sort of.

80
00:04:46,818 --> 00:04:49,254
You sound so sad,
Ella bear.

81
00:04:49,321 --> 00:04:51,189
Grandma--

82
00:04:51,223 --> 00:04:53,458
Look, Ella,
there's no one
keeping you there.

83
00:04:53,525 --> 00:04:56,026
<i>You can do</i>
<i>whatever you want.</i>

84
00:04:56,095 --> 00:04:59,597
The world is open to
all of your dreams.

85
00:05:01,032 --> 00:05:02,600
Whatever that means.
Thanks.

86
00:05:05,137 --> 00:05:07,738
Bye.

87
00:05:07,806 --> 00:05:10,040
[Phone beeps]

88
00:05:10,076 --> 00:05:11,609
Mom?

89
00:05:13,312 --> 00:05:15,246
Mom?

90
00:05:15,314 --> 00:05:18,516
[Thud, clanging]

91
00:05:21,153 --> 00:05:22,653
[sighs]

92
00:05:22,721 --> 00:05:24,422
Mom, I told you not--

93
00:05:24,523 --> 00:05:26,324
Not to climb the ladder.

94
00:05:26,392 --> 00:05:28,293
Your father
isn't around anymore,

95
00:05:28,360 --> 00:05:29,660
And you're too busy,

96
00:05:29,728 --> 00:05:31,762
So how was I supposed
to get my easel?

97
00:05:31,864 --> 00:05:34,531
Plus I found this painting
of Annie's point.

98
00:05:34,633 --> 00:05:36,400
That's great. Now,
get off the ladder
before you hurt yourself.

99
00:05:36,435 --> 00:05:37,836
I still have to get
my easel.

100
00:05:37,903 --> 00:05:39,303
Get off. Step off.

101
00:05:39,371 --> 00:05:40,738
I'll get it.

102
00:05:40,806 --> 00:05:42,006
Come on.

103
00:05:43,309 --> 00:05:44,542
Be careful.

104
00:05:47,279 --> 00:05:48,746
Mom, why are you
limping?

105
00:05:48,813 --> 00:05:50,348
I'm fine.

106
00:05:50,415 --> 00:05:52,216
You could've fallen
off the ladder

107
00:05:52,284 --> 00:05:53,518
And killed yourself.

108
00:05:53,585 --> 00:05:55,319
I didn't fall, and
I'm still on the earth.

109
00:05:55,387 --> 00:05:57,988
Now, will you please
just go up and get
my easel?

110
00:05:59,825 --> 00:06:01,993
I always meant
to finish this one.

111
00:06:02,061 --> 00:06:05,196
I know this is a very
difficult time for you.

112
00:06:05,263 --> 00:06:07,966
But I can't be with you
24 hours a day.

113
00:06:08,033 --> 00:06:10,334
I was asking
for five minutes.

114
00:06:10,402 --> 00:06:12,904
Can't an old woman
get any help around
the house?

115
00:06:13,005 --> 00:06:15,173
How would you feel about
getting an apartment?

116
00:06:15,241 --> 00:06:16,841
Or one of those condos
down by the lake?

117
00:06:16,909 --> 00:06:19,210
This place appraised
for much higher than
you expected.

118
00:06:19,278 --> 00:06:21,479
Your father would
never hear of it.

119
00:06:21,547 --> 00:06:22,880
Mom, this house
is too big for you.

120
00:06:22,948 --> 00:06:25,350
It's my home.

121
00:06:27,085 --> 00:06:28,753
Well, the yard's a mess.

122
00:06:28,821 --> 00:06:30,688
And you left the stove on
twice last week.

123
00:06:30,756 --> 00:06:32,924
Don't speak
to me that way!
I'm your mother.

124
00:06:32,991 --> 00:06:34,191
I'm trying
to be helpful.

125
00:06:34,293 --> 00:06:35,626
No, you're not.

126
00:06:35,694 --> 00:06:37,195
Your father and I
built this house,

127
00:06:37,262 --> 00:06:38,462
And I want
to stay here.

128
00:06:38,531 --> 00:06:39,763
This just
isn't practical.

129
00:06:39,832 --> 00:06:41,365
But I feel
comfortable here.

130
00:06:41,433 --> 00:06:44,601
Mom--
that's enough, Richard!

131
00:06:44,703 --> 00:06:47,005
I'm fine, and I'm not
going anywhere.

132
00:06:47,072 --> 00:06:48,606
Now, if you have
a problem with that,

133
00:06:48,707 --> 00:06:50,641
You should take it up
with your father.

134
00:06:52,944 --> 00:06:56,314
[Playing guitar and humming]

135
00:07:06,425 --> 00:07:07,692
[sighs]

136
00:07:10,696 --> 00:07:12,664
So, what do you
think, mom?

137
00:07:12,731 --> 00:07:16,401
Nursing school or
a songwriting career?

138
00:07:16,468 --> 00:07:19,537
Everybody else seems
to have an opinion.

139
00:07:29,315 --> 00:07:30,314
Here you are.

140
00:07:30,382 --> 00:07:31,783
Thank you.

141
00:07:33,285 --> 00:07:35,319
Oh, Louise!
You won't believe

142
00:07:35,387 --> 00:07:37,321
What I found
in the attic.

143
00:07:37,389 --> 00:07:40,058
My unfinished painting
of Annie's point.

144
00:07:40,125 --> 00:07:42,326
Annie's point? Oh!

145
00:07:42,394 --> 00:07:46,163
That's the place where
you and Eliot wanted
to build a house.

146
00:07:46,231 --> 00:07:48,165
Oh, not just
a house.

147
00:07:48,233 --> 00:07:49,767
Our <i>dream</i> house.

148
00:07:49,835 --> 00:07:51,335
Come on, sweetheart.

149
00:07:51,437 --> 00:07:53,671
We never got to it.

150
00:07:53,739 --> 00:07:55,240
No.

151
00:07:55,307 --> 00:07:57,275
[Dog groans]

152
00:07:57,343 --> 00:08:01,078
I sat in that
hospital room with
Eliot for months.

153
00:08:01,146 --> 00:08:04,048
And then, just a few
minutes before he passed,

154
00:08:04,116 --> 00:08:06,150
He told me his one wish--

155
00:08:06,218 --> 00:08:09,053
To be set free
at Annie's point

156
00:08:09,121 --> 00:08:11,689
On our 50th anniversary.

157
00:08:11,757 --> 00:08:15,159
You have an anniversary
coming up, don't you?

158
00:08:15,227 --> 00:08:16,961
In nine days.

159
00:08:16,996 --> 00:08:18,629
What's holding you back?

160
00:08:21,934 --> 00:08:24,668
You're thinking of
dropping out of college?

161
00:08:26,638 --> 00:08:29,606
Do you have some
sort of plan that
I don't know about?

162
00:08:29,674 --> 00:08:33,645
I want to pursue
a songwriting career.

163
00:08:41,119 --> 00:08:43,120
Ella, you're gonna have
lots and lots of time

164
00:08:43,188 --> 00:08:45,022
For hobbies
and stuff like that
after you graduate.

165
00:08:45,090 --> 00:08:46,557
Right now you've got
to have your degree.

166
00:08:46,625 --> 00:08:48,826
Where did this
songwriting idea
come from, anyway?

167
00:08:48,894 --> 00:08:50,662
I never heard you
sing a note.

168
00:08:50,696 --> 00:08:52,497
Mom did.
Oh.

169
00:08:52,565 --> 00:08:54,999
I see.
Well, trust me--

170
00:08:55,066 --> 00:08:56,701
Even if your mother
was still alive,

171
00:08:56,768 --> 00:08:57,935
You would not
be doing this.

172
00:08:58,003 --> 00:08:59,336
You don't know that.

173
00:08:59,405 --> 00:09:00,471
I've already paid
the tuition,

174
00:09:00,539 --> 00:09:01,673
So please finish out
this year.

175
00:09:01,740 --> 00:09:03,007
Dad, I can't.

176
00:09:03,075 --> 00:09:04,375
Do you have any idea
how much it costs

177
00:09:04,442 --> 00:09:06,343
For me to send you
to this place?

178
00:09:06,411 --> 00:09:08,512
Yeah, I do.
But you don't know
what it's like for me.

179
00:09:08,581 --> 00:09:10,714
Come on, Ella!
It's school!
It's not prison!
Dad!

180
00:09:10,782 --> 00:09:13,250
I know you're going
through some sort of
teenage crisis,

181
00:09:13,352 --> 00:09:15,352
But I am not gonna
let you throw away
your future

182
00:09:15,420 --> 00:09:17,188
To follow some
stupid fantasy!

183
00:09:17,255 --> 00:09:19,390
I knew you wouldn't
understand.

184
00:09:19,457 --> 00:09:21,458
You don't care
about my feelings.

185
00:09:21,526 --> 00:09:23,728
All you care about
is this stupid company.

186
00:09:23,796 --> 00:09:25,229
You don't know what
you're talking about.

187
00:09:25,297 --> 00:09:26,597
This stupid
company is--

188
00:09:26,665 --> 00:09:28,365
Grandma said there was
nothing keeping me there,

189
00:09:28,433 --> 00:09:30,467
And you know what?
She was right.

190
00:09:30,536 --> 00:09:32,336
[Door slams]

191
00:09:36,542 --> 00:09:38,275
Got good news
and bad news.

192
00:09:38,343 --> 00:09:41,578
Your echocardiogram
showed significant blockage
on two of your arteries.

193
00:09:41,646 --> 00:09:44,081
I certainly hope
that's the bad news.

194
00:09:44,149 --> 00:09:45,616
It is.
The good news is,

195
00:09:45,683 --> 00:09:47,318
With a fairly
routine bypass,

196
00:09:47,386 --> 00:09:49,053
You'll be as good
as new. But--

197
00:09:49,121 --> 00:09:52,356
I've never been sick
a day in my life.

198
00:09:52,424 --> 00:09:54,091
But, to be honest,

199
00:09:54,159 --> 00:09:56,260
After watching Eliot
in that hospital
all those months,

200
00:09:56,328 --> 00:09:58,396
I never want to
set foot in one again.

201
00:09:58,464 --> 00:09:59,663
I understand.

202
00:09:59,731 --> 00:10:01,632
But this is
a serious situation.

203
00:10:01,700 --> 00:10:02,833
Without the operation--

204
00:10:02,901 --> 00:10:04,668
I could die?
Yes.

205
00:10:04,703 --> 00:10:06,270
You could die.

206
00:10:06,338 --> 00:10:09,740
We need to get you
into the hospital
as soon as possible.

207
00:10:09,807 --> 00:10:11,942
Can I have
a day or two

208
00:10:12,010 --> 00:10:14,112
Before I commit
to a surgery date?

209
00:10:14,179 --> 00:10:15,947
Sure.

210
00:10:16,014 --> 00:10:17,815
In the meantime,
we need to get you going

211
00:10:17,883 --> 00:10:19,416
On a new blood pressure
medication.

212
00:10:19,484 --> 00:10:21,452
It could make you feel
a little lightheaded
at first,

213
00:10:21,519 --> 00:10:23,086
So try to take it easy.

214
00:10:23,154 --> 00:10:25,590
Can I drive?
I wouldn't recommend it.

215
00:10:25,658 --> 00:10:27,658
At least
not for a while.

216
00:10:27,726 --> 00:10:29,359
Sorry about that, everybody.
What did I miss?

217
00:10:29,428 --> 00:10:30,594
I was just telling
your mother--

218
00:10:30,662 --> 00:10:33,330
I'll fill him in later.
Come on, dear.

219
00:10:33,398 --> 00:10:35,933
Annie... Remember.

220
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:37,234
With this new medication,

221
00:10:37,302 --> 00:10:39,503
No driving if
you feel lightheaded.

222
00:10:39,571 --> 00:10:42,139
Thank you, doctor.

223
00:10:46,979 --> 00:10:50,448
[Guitar playing]

224
00:10:57,389 --> 00:11:00,792
[song ends]

225
00:11:00,859 --> 00:11:03,161
[applause]

226
00:11:05,898 --> 00:11:08,800
Let's hear it again
for Kim Bobletta!

227
00:11:11,469 --> 00:11:15,139
And now please
welcome... Ella.

228
00:11:15,207 --> 00:11:18,109
[Applause]

229
00:11:52,411 --> 00:11:53,811
Sorry. Whoops.

230
00:12:01,453 --> 00:12:03,454
Are you sure Dr. Meldon
didn't say anything else?

231
00:12:03,522 --> 00:12:06,357
It's just blood pressure
medication?

232
00:12:06,425 --> 00:12:07,658
That's all.

233
00:12:07,726 --> 00:12:09,560
But, now that
I can't go alone,

234
00:12:09,627 --> 00:12:11,361
I need you to make
that trip with me.

235
00:12:11,429 --> 00:12:13,030
Mom, that's
2,000 Miles away.

236
00:12:13,065 --> 00:12:14,632
I've got a great car.

237
00:12:14,700 --> 00:12:16,166
I can't do this
right now, mom.

238
00:12:16,234 --> 00:12:18,169
I told you,
there's too much
going on at work.

239
00:12:18,236 --> 00:12:19,570
As soon as
the project is over,

240
00:12:19,638 --> 00:12:20,838
I'll take you there
myself.

241
00:12:20,905 --> 00:12:22,373
That might be too late.

242
00:12:22,440 --> 00:12:24,842
Too late for what?
Mom, what are you
not telling me?

243
00:12:24,909 --> 00:12:27,979
Nothing. But with
the wedding anniversary
coming up--

244
00:12:28,046 --> 00:12:30,581
I'll take you to a nice
dinner to celebrate your
wedding anniversary.

245
00:12:30,649 --> 00:12:31,916
Why don't--oh!

246
00:12:31,984 --> 00:12:33,050
Annie: Oh, my!

247
00:12:38,690 --> 00:12:40,658
Mom!

248
00:12:40,726 --> 00:12:42,360
What if I hadn't
been here?

249
00:12:42,427 --> 00:12:44,395
What would you have done?

250
00:12:44,462 --> 00:12:47,064
Ok, that's it.
You can't stay here
anymore.

251
00:12:47,131 --> 00:12:48,666
This is not just
for my peace of mind.

252
00:12:48,733 --> 00:12:50,067
It's for your safety.

253
00:12:50,134 --> 00:12:51,936
What if you got someone
to stay with me?

254
00:12:52,003 --> 00:12:53,871
For how long?
That's really expensive.

255
00:12:53,939 --> 00:12:55,773
Your father and I
built this house

256
00:12:55,841 --> 00:12:57,775
With our bare hands.

257
00:12:57,842 --> 00:12:59,443
It's all I've got left.

258
00:12:59,510 --> 00:13:01,045
He was my best friend.

259
00:13:01,112 --> 00:13:02,980
We did everything
together.

260
00:13:03,048 --> 00:13:05,983
We were supposed to leave
this earth together.

261
00:13:09,854 --> 00:13:13,457
If I move to that place,
will you make me a promise?

262
00:13:13,524 --> 00:13:14,925
Anything.

263
00:13:14,960 --> 00:13:16,960
You have to take me
to Annie's point. Please.

264
00:13:17,028 --> 00:13:18,496
I already told you,
as soon as--

265
00:13:18,563 --> 00:13:20,097
I need a promise.
I promise.

266
00:13:20,164 --> 00:13:23,100
And it has to be
all of us--
you and me and Ella.

267
00:13:23,168 --> 00:13:24,501
Ok.
And we have to drive.

268
00:13:24,569 --> 00:13:26,804
It'll force you
to spend time with Ella,

269
00:13:26,871 --> 00:13:28,472
Get to know
each other again,

270
00:13:28,540 --> 00:13:30,207
Get to be friends again.

271
00:13:30,275 --> 00:13:32,509
Mom...
Whatever you want.

272
00:13:35,080 --> 00:13:37,548
I've got to go
back to work, ok?

273
00:13:37,615 --> 00:13:39,683
Just call me
if you need anything.

274
00:13:39,751 --> 00:13:42,186
And no stoves,
all right?

275
00:13:43,855 --> 00:13:45,489
I'll see you.

276
00:13:50,528 --> 00:13:52,029
Dad?

277
00:13:52,097 --> 00:13:54,565
Oh!
I'm sorry.

278
00:13:54,632 --> 00:13:56,067
Oh, you should not
sneak up on me.

279
00:13:56,134 --> 00:13:57,501
Dad, I said
I was sorry.

280
00:13:57,569 --> 00:13:59,736
Yeah, but what
I'm telling you--
dad!

281
00:13:59,804 --> 00:14:01,672
It's all right.
What do you need,
honey?

282
00:14:01,739 --> 00:14:03,441
[Sighs]

283
00:14:05,277 --> 00:14:06,877
Do you like
construction?

284
00:14:08,814 --> 00:14:10,714
Uh... Sure.

285
00:14:10,782 --> 00:14:12,850
Did grandpa make you
work with him?

286
00:14:12,918 --> 00:14:16,620
No. No, I think he just
always wanted me to...

287
00:14:16,688 --> 00:14:18,322
Do whatever
made me happy.

288
00:14:18,389 --> 00:14:20,357
He did say his door
would always be open,

289
00:14:20,425 --> 00:14:24,161
And then one day
I just walked in. Why?

290
00:14:24,228 --> 00:14:26,396
Just asking, I guess.

291
00:14:28,667 --> 00:14:31,568
Mom would've been
46 tomorrow.

292
00:14:32,904 --> 00:14:34,304
I know.

293
00:14:38,443 --> 00:14:40,811
Remember the 40th
birthday party
we threw for her?

294
00:14:40,878 --> 00:14:42,045
The surprise party?

295
00:14:42,113 --> 00:14:43,647
Oh, some surprise.
She knew.

296
00:14:43,715 --> 00:14:45,849
Yeah, but she pretended
that she didn't.

297
00:14:45,917 --> 00:14:49,052
Out of all the places
we could've gone,

298
00:14:49,120 --> 00:14:50,521
She wanted to go...

299
00:14:50,589 --> 00:14:52,323
Roller skating.

300
00:14:52,390 --> 00:14:54,725
My knees have never
been the same.

301
00:15:03,535 --> 00:15:05,202
Dad?

302
00:15:05,269 --> 00:15:07,671
I really don't think
that I'm making a mistake.

303
00:15:09,341 --> 00:15:11,875
To tell you the truth,
I'm not really sure
what you're doing.

304
00:15:11,944 --> 00:15:13,777
I know I have
some talent with music.

305
00:15:13,845 --> 00:15:17,113
I just don't know--

306
00:15:17,182 --> 00:15:19,082
[cell phone rings]
[sighs]

307
00:15:19,150 --> 00:15:20,217
Sorry.

308
00:15:22,788 --> 00:15:24,221
Hello?

309
00:15:24,289 --> 00:15:26,090
Oh, yes, Mr. Backis.

310
00:15:26,158 --> 00:15:29,226
No, no. We've avoided
that with Mr. Nucci.

311
00:15:29,394 --> 00:15:31,996
Tomorrow? Um...

312
00:15:32,030 --> 00:15:33,563
I'm supposed
to bring my mother

313
00:15:33,631 --> 00:15:35,933
To a retirement
community tomorrow.

314
00:15:36,001 --> 00:15:38,736
Mr. Backis, can I
call you back?

315
00:15:38,803 --> 00:15:40,704
Thank you.

316
00:15:40,772 --> 00:15:42,339
Ok, bye.

317
00:15:44,509 --> 00:15:46,043
Do you want me
to go with grandma

318
00:15:46,111 --> 00:15:47,277
To her new place?

319
00:15:47,345 --> 00:15:50,047
It's not just
the work, Ella.

320
00:15:50,115 --> 00:15:52,249
It's...

321
00:15:52,317 --> 00:15:55,552
I understand.
I'll go with her.

322
00:15:59,023 --> 00:16:00,958
Annie: I don't know
if Richard's gonna
keep his promise.

323
00:16:01,025 --> 00:16:03,194
Maybe I should just
pack the car up

324
00:16:03,261 --> 00:16:05,662
And head out
to Annie's point.

325
00:16:05,730 --> 00:16:07,698
It's ridiculous,
isn't it?

326
00:16:09,201 --> 00:16:13,036
I know I made
that promise to you.

327
00:16:13,105 --> 00:16:16,974
I'm just not sure
how I'm going to
pull it off.

328
00:16:16,975 --> 00:16:20,677
Well, we'll talk
more about this
in the morning.

329
00:16:25,750 --> 00:16:28,052
Good night, my love.

330
00:16:36,794 --> 00:16:38,795
You have all your pills?

331
00:16:38,864 --> 00:16:41,165
Yes, Richard.

332
00:16:41,233 --> 00:16:43,033
I wish I could drive you
to the orientation.

333
00:16:43,101 --> 00:16:44,501
That's ok.

334
00:16:44,569 --> 00:16:46,237
It's just that
I canceled on these
guys yesterday.

335
00:16:46,304 --> 00:16:47,872
I said it's ok.

336
00:16:47,939 --> 00:16:49,640
I know this is
all happening
really fast,

337
00:16:49,707 --> 00:16:51,041
But you're gonna
like the place,
I know you will.

338
00:16:51,109 --> 00:16:52,409
And just think--
you're gonna be

339
00:16:52,477 --> 00:16:53,811
Practically neighbors
with Louise.

340
00:16:53,879 --> 00:16:55,212
I'm gonna be fine.

341
00:16:55,280 --> 00:16:56,981
Are you gonna be
ok to drive?

342
00:16:57,048 --> 00:16:59,349
Ella's here.
I'll be fine.

343
00:16:59,417 --> 00:17:01,685
Richard: All right.
So, I'll, uh...

344
00:17:01,753 --> 00:17:03,720
I'll stop in later tonight
to get you settled.

345
00:17:03,789 --> 00:17:05,189
Thank you.

346
00:17:12,063 --> 00:17:13,263
You're a good son.

347
00:17:13,331 --> 00:17:14,431
Thanks, mom.

348
00:17:29,915 --> 00:17:31,181
Hey.

349
00:17:31,249 --> 00:17:33,417
Make a right here,
grandma.

350
00:17:46,231 --> 00:17:49,533
Gramm, you were supposed
to turn right there.

351
00:17:49,568 --> 00:17:52,068
I probably should've
told your father.

352
00:17:52,136 --> 00:17:54,371
I'm not moving in
there today.

353
00:17:54,406 --> 00:17:56,539
What are you
talking about?

354
00:17:56,607 --> 00:17:59,977
I thought about it.
I did.

355
00:18:00,044 --> 00:18:02,812
But I truly
can't remember

356
00:18:02,881 --> 00:18:05,015
What Annie's point
looked like.

357
00:18:05,083 --> 00:18:08,052
And I need to be there
for my anniversary.

358
00:18:08,119 --> 00:18:10,520
I'm going to California.

359
00:18:10,588 --> 00:18:12,322
And I need you
to go with me.

360
00:18:12,357 --> 00:18:15,292
What?
We're going
to California.

361
00:18:15,393 --> 00:18:16,593
I can't.

362
00:18:16,660 --> 00:18:18,728
Give me one
good reason why not.

363
00:18:18,830 --> 00:18:20,130
My father.

364
00:18:20,198 --> 00:18:21,898
Oh, I can handle him.

365
00:18:21,966 --> 00:18:24,901
What are you gonna do,
stay here, pay rent,

366
00:18:24,969 --> 00:18:27,804
Mope around? You want
to be a songwriter.

367
00:18:27,872 --> 00:18:30,073
You have to have
something to write about.

368
00:18:30,141 --> 00:18:31,508
It's not that easy.

369
00:18:31,609 --> 00:18:34,078
You wouldn't want me to
drive there by myself,
would you?

370
00:18:34,145 --> 00:18:35,479
That's not fair.

371
00:18:35,580 --> 00:18:36,680
I'm an old lady.

372
00:18:36,748 --> 00:18:39,783
I'd be all alone
for 2,000 Miles.

373
00:18:39,885 --> 00:18:41,151
And all I have
is an old map.

374
00:18:41,219 --> 00:18:42,252
Grandma!

375
00:18:42,320 --> 00:18:44,154
I'm also on this
new medication.

376
00:18:44,289 --> 00:18:46,624
I'm not even sure
I can drive on my own.

377
00:18:46,691 --> 00:18:49,293
I don't have my guitar
or any of my clothes.

378
00:18:49,361 --> 00:18:50,694
Oh, we can get those.

379
00:18:50,762 --> 00:18:52,463
I have plenty of cash.

380
00:18:52,530 --> 00:18:54,364
And there are always
credit cards.

381
00:18:58,069 --> 00:18:59,936
Thank you, Ella bear.

382
00:19:05,110 --> 00:19:07,277
Come on, Ella.

383
00:19:08,446 --> 00:19:10,614
Let's live a little.

384
00:19:53,824 --> 00:19:55,892
I thought you said
you couldn't drive.

385
00:19:55,960 --> 00:19:58,595
It's just a little
further up this way.

386
00:20:00,598 --> 00:20:02,265
Put that book down
for a second,

387
00:20:02,333 --> 00:20:06,002
And grab that
small painting
behind your seat.

388
00:20:10,441 --> 00:20:12,309
We weren't
much older than you

389
00:20:12,377 --> 00:20:14,811
When grandpa moved us
from California

390
00:20:14,879 --> 00:20:17,047
For a job he just
couldn't pass up.

391
00:20:17,082 --> 00:20:20,283
We didn't have
a penny to our name.

392
00:20:20,318 --> 00:20:22,719
But we had the world
in front of us.

393
00:20:22,787 --> 00:20:25,155
And those trees.

394
00:20:25,223 --> 00:20:29,193
They were like
a row of soldiers
welcoming us home.

395
00:20:29,260 --> 00:20:32,028
What did you leave
back in California?

396
00:20:32,096 --> 00:20:33,530
Everything.

397
00:20:33,598 --> 00:20:37,100
My parents,
my baby brother,
you name it.

398
00:20:37,202 --> 00:20:39,402
What happened with
your little brother?

399
00:20:39,537 --> 00:20:42,339
We'll have plenty
of time for that.

400
00:20:46,210 --> 00:20:49,146
If I'm not mistaken,
this should be it.

401
00:21:02,294 --> 00:21:04,627
Ella: What happened
to the trees?

402
00:21:04,696 --> 00:21:06,930
This is it.

403
00:21:06,998 --> 00:21:08,499
Grandma,
this is stupid.

404
00:21:08,566 --> 00:21:11,068
We can just barge in
on some strangers.

405
00:21:11,136 --> 00:21:13,103
It'll be fine.

406
00:21:13,171 --> 00:21:14,738
People are nicer
than you think.

407
00:21:16,474 --> 00:21:17,941
I'll do the talking.

408
00:21:18,009 --> 00:21:19,910
Good, 'cause I don't
want to be here.

409
00:21:22,213 --> 00:21:23,914
[Spraying]

410
00:21:25,817 --> 00:21:27,417
Gotcha!

411
00:21:27,485 --> 00:21:29,185
Uh...

412
00:21:29,254 --> 00:21:30,754
Who are you?

413
00:21:30,821 --> 00:21:34,190
Is your mother
or father home?

414
00:21:34,259 --> 00:21:36,393
Mom?!

415
00:21:36,461 --> 00:21:39,596
Two strange ladies
are here!

416
00:21:39,664 --> 00:21:40,931
That's a good start.

417
00:21:40,998 --> 00:21:42,266
I'm leaving.
Uh--

418
00:21:45,036 --> 00:21:47,037
Can I help you?
Hi.

419
00:21:47,105 --> 00:21:49,239
My name is Annie Eason,

420
00:21:49,307 --> 00:21:51,341
And this is
my granddaughter Ella.

421
00:21:51,443 --> 00:21:52,709
Can I help you?

422
00:21:52,777 --> 00:21:55,178
I know this is gonna
sound unusual, but...

423
00:21:55,280 --> 00:21:58,615
My husband and I
built this house
years ago,

424
00:21:58,682 --> 00:22:02,619
And I was wondering
if it would be possible...

425
00:22:02,687 --> 00:22:05,122
For me to have
a look inside.

426
00:22:05,189 --> 00:22:07,890
We should be going.
Sorry to bother you.

427
00:22:07,958 --> 00:22:09,993
You see,
we left something

428
00:22:10,060 --> 00:22:12,795
Behind the nook
in the kitchen, for luck.

429
00:22:12,863 --> 00:22:14,864
Would it be all right
for me to see

430
00:22:14,932 --> 00:22:16,766
If it's still there?

431
00:22:16,834 --> 00:22:18,468
I don't know.

432
00:22:18,536 --> 00:22:20,570
Mrs. Hogan...
My granddaughter and I

433
00:22:20,572 --> 00:22:22,905
Are on a Journey
across the country,

434
00:22:22,941 --> 00:22:24,975
And I have
a heart problem.

435
00:22:25,043 --> 00:22:29,179
So I figured we could
use all the luck
we could get.

436
00:22:29,246 --> 00:22:31,915
We built the house
in 1960.

437
00:22:31,982 --> 00:22:34,117
How long have you
been living here?

438
00:22:34,185 --> 00:22:35,485
[Baby crying]

439
00:22:35,553 --> 00:22:38,355
Um, five years
this July.

440
00:22:39,924 --> 00:22:42,225
I hope you don't
mind my asking--

441
00:22:42,327 --> 00:22:45,195
What happened
to those beautiful
trees out front?

442
00:22:45,262 --> 00:22:47,631
This is how the house
came to us.

443
00:22:57,008 --> 00:22:59,910
Are--are you sure
you know what
you're looking for?

444
00:23:00,011 --> 00:23:01,744
Annie: I'm sure.

445
00:23:07,852 --> 00:23:09,453
Mrs. Hogan:
Oh, my goodness.

446
00:23:09,520 --> 00:23:10,987
Ella: What is that?

447
00:23:11,055 --> 00:23:14,391
Annie: A 1919
gold Liberty coin...

448
00:23:14,459 --> 00:23:18,094
Given to your grandfather
by his father.

449
00:23:18,162 --> 00:23:20,564
When we left California,
he said,

450
00:23:20,631 --> 00:23:23,266
"hide it someplace
in your first home,

451
00:23:23,334 --> 00:23:25,802
And it'll bring you
a lifetime of happiness."

452
00:23:25,870 --> 00:23:28,238
We call it lucky 19.

453
00:23:28,305 --> 00:23:31,241
Just before he passed,
your grandfather said

454
00:23:31,308 --> 00:23:35,612
He realized this coin
needed to come back
to the family.

455
00:23:35,713 --> 00:23:40,183
Houses don't need luck.
People do.

456
00:23:45,289 --> 00:23:47,257
Margaret, I cannot
thank you enough

457
00:23:47,324 --> 00:23:48,859
For allowing us
in your home.

458
00:23:48,927 --> 00:23:50,493
It's my pleasure.

459
00:23:50,562 --> 00:23:52,963
Hold on a second.

460
00:24:02,573 --> 00:24:04,607
I want you
to have this.

461
00:24:06,444 --> 00:24:07,810
This isn't
<i>this</i> house, is it?

462
00:24:07,878 --> 00:24:09,446
It sure is.

463
00:24:09,514 --> 00:24:11,881
There used to be
trees here.

464
00:24:11,983 --> 00:24:14,084
It was so beautiful.

465
00:24:15,553 --> 00:24:17,120
I can't accept this.

466
00:24:17,188 --> 00:24:18,989
Oh, it would mean
a great deal to me

467
00:24:19,056 --> 00:24:22,259
If you could use
some of that money to
plant some new trees.

468
00:24:22,326 --> 00:24:23,927
I can't.

469
00:24:23,995 --> 00:24:25,295
I insist.

470
00:24:25,363 --> 00:24:26,763
Thank you again.

471
00:24:26,798 --> 00:24:29,165
No. Thank <i>you.</i>

472
00:24:29,234 --> 00:24:31,034
[Baby crying]

473
00:24:31,102 --> 00:24:33,503
Oh... There he is again.

474
00:24:33,605 --> 00:24:35,772
I'm so sorry.
Have a great trip.

475
00:24:35,840 --> 00:24:38,241
Sam!

476
00:24:38,309 --> 00:24:40,410
I can't believe you just
gave her all that money.

477
00:24:40,478 --> 00:24:43,580
Oh, your grandfather
would want the house

478
00:24:43,648 --> 00:24:46,750
To look like it did
when we were younger.

479
00:24:46,818 --> 00:24:49,152
Besides, it makes
you feel good

480
00:24:49,219 --> 00:24:51,488
To do things
for other people.

481
00:24:51,556 --> 00:24:53,189
Whatever.

482
00:24:55,660 --> 00:24:57,861
And what did you mean
when you said

483
00:24:57,929 --> 00:25:00,564
You had a heart problem?

484
00:25:00,631 --> 00:25:02,766
Didn't I tell you?

485
00:25:02,834 --> 00:25:05,902
Um... I need
bypass surgery.

486
00:25:05,937 --> 00:25:07,337
What?!

487
00:25:07,405 --> 00:25:09,472
Why wouldn't you
tell me that?

488
00:25:09,540 --> 00:25:12,642
You wouldn't have
agreed to come
with me if I had.

489
00:25:12,709 --> 00:25:14,277
Besides,
I feel great.

490
00:25:20,751 --> 00:25:23,353
<i>[Rock music on radio]</i>

491
00:25:25,889 --> 00:25:26,990
[turns radio off]

492
00:25:27,058 --> 00:25:29,492
Do you have
a boyfriend?

493
00:25:29,560 --> 00:25:31,027
No.

494
00:25:31,095 --> 00:25:33,163
Had many dates lately?

495
00:25:33,197 --> 00:25:33,863
No.

496
00:25:33,998 --> 00:25:35,331
In my day...

497
00:25:35,399 --> 00:25:37,367
A man would take you
to the movies,

498
00:25:37,434 --> 00:25:39,168
Or for a soda,

499
00:25:39,236 --> 00:25:40,470
And if he
interested you,

500
00:25:40,538 --> 00:25:42,238
You'd spend
some time together.

501
00:25:42,340 --> 00:25:43,373
But after a few months,

502
00:25:43,441 --> 00:25:45,942
If he wasn't serious
about marriage,

503
00:25:45,977 --> 00:25:48,010
You'd move on
to a man who was.

504
00:25:48,078 --> 00:25:50,112
Kind of sounds like
an arranged marriage.

505
00:25:50,181 --> 00:25:52,716
[Laughs]
in lots of ways, it was.

506
00:25:52,783 --> 00:25:54,317
Your grandpa
asked me to marry him

507
00:25:54,385 --> 00:25:55,852
On our fifth date.

508
00:25:55,920 --> 00:25:58,689
Women didn't have
the freedom that you have.

509
00:25:58,723 --> 00:26:00,524
Some freedom. I've never
been on a second date,

510
00:26:00,591 --> 00:26:01,991
Let alone a fifth.

511
00:26:02,059 --> 00:26:04,794
You are a beautiful,
talented young woman.
Why not?

512
00:26:04,862 --> 00:26:06,830
I'd rather not discuss
my love life

513
00:26:06,897 --> 00:26:08,365
With my grandma.

514
00:26:08,432 --> 00:26:09,866
Doesn't sound like
there <i>is</i> a love life.

515
00:26:09,933 --> 00:26:12,035
Even more reason
to end the discussion.

516
00:26:12,103 --> 00:26:14,270
So, to answer
your question, no.

517
00:26:14,339 --> 00:26:17,974
No one is "courting me"
at the moment.

518
00:26:18,076 --> 00:26:21,011
<i>%% ...The earth was</i>
<i>nowhere to be found %%</i>

519
00:26:21,078 --> 00:26:23,212
<i>%% and the view from-- %%</i>

520
00:26:23,281 --> 00:26:24,714
Why do you think you
don't have a boyfriend?

521
00:26:24,782 --> 00:26:26,883
Grandma, please!

522
00:26:30,822 --> 00:26:32,689
It's like with my music.

523
00:26:32,757 --> 00:26:34,424
I'm in my room,
and I'm fine.

524
00:26:34,492 --> 00:26:36,526
But you get me in front
of a crowd, and I freeze.

525
00:26:36,593 --> 00:26:38,195
Same thing with guys.

526
00:26:38,262 --> 00:26:40,797
I get totally terrified
when I talk to them.

527
00:26:40,864 --> 00:26:42,566
You're just
not flirting enough.

528
00:26:42,633 --> 00:26:43,967
I don't know
how to flirt.

529
00:26:44,035 --> 00:26:47,070
Nonsense. Everyone
knows how to flirt.

530
00:26:47,171 --> 00:26:48,471
Not me.

531
00:26:48,573 --> 00:26:51,241
<i>[Country music playing]</i>

532
00:26:51,308 --> 00:26:52,909
Whatever.

533
00:26:57,814 --> 00:26:59,349
Mom?

534
00:27:33,317 --> 00:27:34,951
[Phone ringing]

535
00:27:36,487 --> 00:27:38,555
[ring]

536
00:27:39,957 --> 00:27:41,558
Hello?

537
00:27:41,625 --> 00:27:43,359
<i>Woman: Good evening.</i>
<i>This is Dr. Meldon's</i>
<i>office.</i>

538
00:27:43,427 --> 00:27:44,860
<i>Is Annie Eason</i>
<i>available?</i>

539
00:27:44,928 --> 00:27:46,596
No, I'm sorry, she's not.
This is her son Richard.

540
00:27:46,663 --> 00:27:47,997
Is there anything
I can do?

541
00:27:48,065 --> 00:27:49,665
<i>Dr. Meldon wanted</i>
<i>to make sure</i>

542
00:27:49,733 --> 00:27:51,801
<i>That she scheduled</i>
<i>her surgery as soon</i>
<i>as possible.</i>

543
00:27:51,868 --> 00:27:54,870
Surgery? What surgery?

544
00:27:54,938 --> 00:27:57,740
<i>Oh, I'm sorry.</i>
<i>I thought Dr. Meldon</i>
<i>told you</i>

545
00:27:57,808 --> 00:28:00,443
<i>That Annie needs</i>
<i>heart surgery</i>
<i>as soon as possible.</i>

546
00:28:02,146 --> 00:28:04,314
<i>%% Wished upon a star %%</i>

547
00:28:04,382 --> 00:28:06,215
<i>%% for a mansion</i>
<i>or a Learjet %%</i>

548
00:28:06,284 --> 00:28:08,151
<i>%% or some fancy car %%</i>

549
00:28:08,218 --> 00:28:10,387
<i>%% so I never</i>
<i>quite believed %%</i>

550
00:28:10,454 --> 00:28:13,490
<i>%% that miracles</i>
<i>came true %%</i>

551
00:28:13,557 --> 00:28:16,660
<i>%% then there was you... %%</i>

552
00:28:16,727 --> 00:28:21,097
%% 'cause I believe
in miracles tonight %%

553
00:28:21,165 --> 00:28:23,433
%% I think you're
an Angel %%

554
00:28:23,501 --> 00:28:25,268
%% fit to
hold me tight %%

555
00:28:25,336 --> 00:28:27,637
%% it seems my life's
a fairy tale %%

556
00:28:27,705 --> 00:28:30,339
%% 'cause it always
comes out right %%

557
00:28:30,341 --> 00:28:33,777
%% and I believe
in miracles %%

558
00:28:33,844 --> 00:28:35,678
%% tonight %%

559
00:28:35,746 --> 00:28:37,246
[applause]

560
00:28:37,348 --> 00:28:38,381
[laughs]

561
00:28:38,448 --> 00:28:40,884
There are people here,
grandma!

562
00:28:40,951 --> 00:28:44,387
Oh, come on, girl.
Live it up.

563
00:28:44,454 --> 00:28:45,722
Oh, this is
so embarrassing.

564
00:28:45,790 --> 00:28:47,090
Please sit down.

565
00:28:48,659 --> 00:28:50,626
Put down that notebook
for five minutes

566
00:28:50,695 --> 00:28:51,861
And live a little.

567
00:28:51,929 --> 00:28:53,529
This notebook
is my life.

568
00:28:53,631 --> 00:28:55,364
What are you writing?

569
00:28:55,432 --> 00:28:57,634
A song. What else
would I be writing?

570
00:28:57,701 --> 00:28:59,201
How am I
supposed to know?

571
00:28:59,269 --> 00:29:01,303
You never let anyone
look at that thing.

572
00:29:01,372 --> 00:29:03,639
What's the song about?
Nothing.

573
00:29:03,674 --> 00:29:05,408
Sounds like a hit.

574
00:29:05,476 --> 00:29:06,942
May I see it?

575
00:29:07,011 --> 00:29:08,110
I'd rather not.

576
00:29:08,178 --> 00:29:10,347
Oh, please, come on.

577
00:29:20,157 --> 00:29:22,525
These are great.

578
00:29:22,592 --> 00:29:24,227
None of them
are done yet.

579
00:29:24,294 --> 00:29:26,128
How does this one go?

580
00:29:26,197 --> 00:29:27,898
I'm not gonna sing
for you.

581
00:29:27,932 --> 00:29:29,766
Then I will.

582
00:29:29,834 --> 00:29:32,502
%% When you find that
special someone-- %%

583
00:29:32,570 --> 00:29:34,504
Ok, ok, if--
if I sing,

584
00:29:34,572 --> 00:29:36,639
Will you stop
embarrassing me?

585
00:29:36,707 --> 00:29:39,075
You know I can't
promise you that.

586
00:29:41,245 --> 00:29:43,613
You sing, I'll stop.
Ok?

587
00:29:45,349 --> 00:29:47,784
I can't believe
I'm gonna do this.

588
00:29:55,459 --> 00:30:00,296
%% Find that someone
special %%

589
00:30:00,364 --> 00:30:06,202
%% give him love,
make him your own %%

590
00:30:06,237 --> 00:30:07,870
%% stop your search %%

591
00:30:07,938 --> 00:30:10,706
%% and you will find %%

592
00:30:10,775 --> 00:30:15,545
%% that your heart
has found its home %%

593
00:30:17,314 --> 00:30:18,715
Man: Hey.

594
00:30:18,749 --> 00:30:20,516
You some kind of
singer or something?

595
00:30:20,618 --> 00:30:21,818
No.

596
00:30:21,886 --> 00:30:23,787
Yes, she is.

597
00:30:23,854 --> 00:30:25,922
And someday
you're gonna want
her autograph.

598
00:30:26,023 --> 00:30:29,225
Man: If you ever record
that little song of yours...

599
00:30:29,293 --> 00:30:32,128
I'll tell you what--
I'd buy it.

600
00:30:34,966 --> 00:30:36,833
You ladies have a
lovely evening.

601
00:30:40,237 --> 00:30:42,571
Now, those were
real men.

602
00:30:42,607 --> 00:30:44,340
And they really
liked your style.

603
00:30:44,408 --> 00:30:45,508
Heh!

604
00:30:45,576 --> 00:30:49,245
And it's good
to see you smile.

605
00:30:49,280 --> 00:30:50,446
[Sighs]

606
00:30:50,514 --> 00:30:52,815
[cell phone ringing]

607
00:30:54,952 --> 00:30:56,585
It's my dad.

608
00:30:56,654 --> 00:30:59,889
He had to call
sometime.

609
00:30:59,957 --> 00:31:02,659
I don't know how to
use these things!

610
00:31:02,726 --> 00:31:04,493
Press the green button.

611
00:31:06,864 --> 00:31:08,731
[Beep]

612
00:31:08,799 --> 00:31:10,033
Hello?

613
00:31:10,100 --> 00:31:12,035
Mom? Where are you?

614
00:31:12,102 --> 00:31:14,503
I'm not telling.

615
00:31:14,605 --> 00:31:16,439
Mom, I talked
to Dr. Meldon.

616
00:31:16,507 --> 00:31:18,241
I know about the surgery.
This is serious.

617
00:31:18,309 --> 00:31:19,909
You cannot just
pick up and leave.

618
00:31:20,011 --> 00:31:21,511
I can,
and I did.

619
00:31:21,579 --> 00:31:23,580
Is Ella with you?
<i>She sure is.</i>

620
00:31:23,647 --> 00:31:25,147
When are you
coming home?

621
00:31:25,215 --> 00:31:26,516
We're not.

622
00:31:26,583 --> 00:31:28,584
<i>Be reasonable.</i>
<i>You're sick.</i>
I feel fine.

623
00:31:28,653 --> 00:31:30,987
I cannot go chasing
all over the country
for you.

624
00:31:31,055 --> 00:31:32,421
<i>Then don't.</i>

625
00:31:32,490 --> 00:31:34,089
I'm sorry
I lied to you,

626
00:31:34,157 --> 00:31:36,659
But I--I didn't know
any other way.

627
00:31:36,761 --> 00:31:38,294
Please don't do this.

628
00:31:38,362 --> 00:31:40,196
<i>We love you,</i>
<i>and we'll call you</i>
<i>tomorrow.</i>

629
00:31:40,264 --> 00:31:42,198
And don't sell
my house!

630
00:31:42,266 --> 00:31:43,867
'Cause I'm not
moving.

631
00:31:43,935 --> 00:31:45,702
<i>[Click]</i>

632
00:31:45,769 --> 00:31:47,837
He's gonna be mad.

633
00:31:47,905 --> 00:31:49,605
He already is.

634
00:31:55,179 --> 00:31:57,547
[Dialing]

635
00:32:07,892 --> 00:32:09,025
Hello?

636
00:32:09,093 --> 00:32:10,459
Yes. Yes, good evening.

637
00:32:10,527 --> 00:32:15,198
Um... I need
a bit of assistance.

638
00:32:31,782 --> 00:32:33,549
Annie: I'm getting
a little tired.

639
00:32:33,617 --> 00:32:35,518
I think I'll
let you drive.

640
00:32:35,585 --> 00:32:37,753
Let's find
an ATM machine.

641
00:32:37,788 --> 00:32:40,123
What's your pin?

642
00:32:40,191 --> 00:32:41,991
Take a guess.

643
00:32:42,059 --> 00:32:43,193
19?

644
00:32:43,260 --> 00:32:45,261
1919. You got it.

645
00:32:51,202 --> 00:32:53,002
[Beeping]

646
00:32:54,804 --> 00:32:56,339
You don't have
any money.

647
00:32:56,407 --> 00:32:57,140
Try it again.

648
00:32:59,744 --> 00:33:02,278
[Beeping]

649
00:33:02,346 --> 00:33:03,680
Same thing.

650
00:33:03,781 --> 00:33:05,949
Well, it must be
the machine.

651
00:33:16,327 --> 00:33:18,361
What happened?

652
00:33:18,429 --> 00:33:20,396
My credit card
was declined, too.

653
00:33:20,464 --> 00:33:23,666
I just gave him
our last $25 for gas.

654
00:33:23,733 --> 00:33:25,534
You're kidding, right?

655
00:33:25,602 --> 00:33:27,570
No, Ella, I'm not.

656
00:33:27,637 --> 00:33:30,273
Great. We have no money
to get across country...

657
00:33:30,341 --> 00:33:32,875
But that poor family
has $500 to buy trees

658
00:33:32,943 --> 00:33:34,643
That they're never
gonna plant!

659
00:33:34,711 --> 00:33:36,745
Stop it, Ella.

660
00:33:36,814 --> 00:33:38,981
We're in a bit of
a pickle, that's all.

661
00:33:39,049 --> 00:33:40,349
That's it.
I'm calling my dad.

662
00:33:40,417 --> 00:33:42,551
Save your breath.
I'll call him.

663
00:33:42,653 --> 00:33:44,253
[Sighs]

664
00:33:44,321 --> 00:33:45,855
[phone beeps]

665
00:33:51,295 --> 00:33:53,529
[cell phone ringing]

666
00:33:56,166 --> 00:33:57,667
Mom?

667
00:33:57,735 --> 00:33:59,768
Just because you
don't agree with me,

668
00:33:59,836 --> 00:34:02,005
You don't have to
sabotage our trip.

669
00:34:02,006 --> 00:34:03,206
Tell me where you are,

670
00:34:03,273 --> 00:34:04,740
And I'll reactivate
your credit cards.

671
00:34:04,842 --> 00:34:06,475
You can't reactive it.

672
00:34:06,577 --> 00:34:07,910
I <i>have to</i>
<i>reactivate it.</i>

673
00:34:07,978 --> 00:34:09,846
In person.
You know that.

674
00:34:09,913 --> 00:34:11,413
What was I
supposed to do?

675
00:34:11,482 --> 00:34:13,816
Honor the dying wish
of your father.

676
00:34:13,884 --> 00:34:16,052
Mom, I want you
to turn around
and come back home.

677
00:34:16,120 --> 00:34:17,654
To what home?

678
00:34:17,755 --> 00:34:20,523
I'm in good company.
I'm not coming back.

679
00:34:20,591 --> 00:34:22,458
Are you at least taking
your medication?

680
00:34:22,526 --> 00:34:24,093
If you're so concerned
about me,

681
00:34:24,195 --> 00:34:25,795
How come you're
leaving me penniless?

682
00:34:25,863 --> 00:34:27,730
Tell me where you are,
and I'll wire you
some money.

683
00:34:27,798 --> 00:34:29,765
Oh, nice try.

684
00:34:29,834 --> 00:34:32,035
Ok, may I please
speak with Ella?

685
00:34:32,102 --> 00:34:33,369
She's not here.

686
00:34:33,437 --> 00:34:35,171
<i>Richard:</i>
<i>Where is she?</i>

687
00:34:35,239 --> 00:34:37,573
She's out getting
a gigantic tattoo

688
00:34:37,641 --> 00:34:39,208
Of a dragon
on her back.

689
00:34:39,276 --> 00:34:41,610
Ella wouldn't do that.
<i>Yes, she would.</i>

690
00:34:41,712 --> 00:34:45,814
And I'm getting
a skull and crossbones
on my butt.

691
00:34:45,850 --> 00:34:48,217
<i>Mom, are you</i>
<i>coming home or not?</i>

692
00:34:48,285 --> 00:34:51,087
<i>Not. It's lucky for you</i>
<i>we're flesh and blood...</i>

693
00:34:51,155 --> 00:34:54,123
Because what you've done
is almost unforgivable.

694
00:34:54,191 --> 00:34:55,224
[Hangs up]

695
00:34:57,027 --> 00:34:58,727
Why did you do that?!

696
00:34:58,796 --> 00:35:00,129
Because I'm
a grown woman

697
00:35:00,197 --> 00:35:01,964
Who can take care
of herself.

698
00:35:01,966 --> 00:35:03,299
Now, get driving,
Ella bear.

699
00:35:03,367 --> 00:35:04,934
We have to make
some money.

700
00:35:05,002 --> 00:35:06,936
No, my dad is right.
You need surgery,

701
00:35:07,004 --> 00:35:10,106
And we don't
have any money.
We have to go back.

702
00:35:12,575 --> 00:35:14,710
Eliot, I made you
a promise.

703
00:35:14,778 --> 00:35:17,880
And nothing is going
to stand in the way
of my keeping it.

704
00:35:18,015 --> 00:35:19,883
You can count on me.

705
00:35:22,753 --> 00:35:26,121
Ella, I'm making it
to Annie's point,
with or without you.

706
00:35:26,223 --> 00:35:27,256
If you want to come
with me,

707
00:35:27,323 --> 00:35:29,025
You're gonna have to
play by my rules.

708
00:35:33,530 --> 00:35:35,198
Woman: Could you
please pick up?

709
00:35:35,265 --> 00:35:37,166
This is important.
Pick up for one sec.

710
00:35:37,234 --> 00:35:39,768
Brenda,
something's come up.
I have to leave town.

711
00:35:39,836 --> 00:35:41,471
I'm gonna have both
cell phones with me.

712
00:35:41,538 --> 00:35:42,605
But don't use
the personal number

713
00:35:42,672 --> 00:35:43,973
Unless you
absolutely have to,

714
00:35:44,041 --> 00:35:45,208
And transfer all
my business calls

715
00:35:45,276 --> 00:35:46,743
To the business
number. Got it?

716
00:35:46,810 --> 00:35:48,111
Honey, I've been here
for eight years.

717
00:35:48,178 --> 00:35:50,079
I think I've got it.
Where are you going?

718
00:35:50,147 --> 00:35:51,981
I'm not quite sure.
But I need you to
do me another favor.

719
00:35:52,049 --> 00:35:53,415
Could you find out
where the last place

720
00:35:53,483 --> 00:35:55,051
That credit card
number was used?

721
00:35:55,085 --> 00:35:56,619
And you've got to call
Backis and Weller

722
00:35:56,686 --> 00:35:58,620
And tell them I can't
make today's appointment.

723
00:35:58,688 --> 00:36:00,222
You can tell them
yourself.

724
00:36:00,290 --> 00:36:01,958
I was trying to tell you--
they're here early.

725
00:36:03,928 --> 00:36:05,861
Man: I've been here
a lot longer than I planned,

726
00:36:05,930 --> 00:36:08,231
But I want those contracts
on my desk by 4:00.

727
00:36:10,934 --> 00:36:12,935
[Sighs]

728
00:36:13,003 --> 00:36:14,470
Mr. Backis.

729
00:36:14,505 --> 00:36:16,339
Mr. Weller,
I am terribly sorry.

730
00:36:16,406 --> 00:36:18,207
But we're gonna have to
postpone today's meeting.

731
00:36:18,275 --> 00:36:19,842
Something's come up,
and I have to leave town.

732
00:36:19,909 --> 00:36:21,610
Richard, let me
level with you.

733
00:36:21,678 --> 00:36:23,346
Eason's line of credit

734
00:36:23,413 --> 00:36:26,182
Is what we call
in the banking industry
"guarded".

735
00:36:26,249 --> 00:36:28,717
Well, I'll take that
into consideration.

736
00:36:28,785 --> 00:36:30,386
Now, if you'd like to
make a new appointment,

737
00:36:30,454 --> 00:36:31,787
You can do that
with my assistant.

738
00:36:31,855 --> 00:36:35,024
And, again, my apologies
for the inconvenience.

739
00:36:35,092 --> 00:36:38,427
Uh, Mr. Eason? Are you
still going out of town?

740
00:36:38,429 --> 00:36:40,696
Absolutely.

741
00:36:48,405 --> 00:36:51,273
You gonna stay mad at me
the entire trip?

742
00:36:54,711 --> 00:36:57,880
I can go longer than
you can without talking.

743
00:36:57,948 --> 00:37:00,049
We'll start right now.

744
00:37:00,150 --> 00:37:02,151
No one is talking.

745
00:37:02,219 --> 00:37:04,586
Over 1,000 Miles to go,

746
00:37:04,655 --> 00:37:06,989
And no one is talking.

747
00:37:07,091 --> 00:37:08,424
Oh, we're smiling now.

748
00:37:08,492 --> 00:37:10,059
But no one is talking.

749
00:37:10,126 --> 00:37:12,829
You couldn't go
five minutes
without talking.

750
00:37:12,896 --> 00:37:14,697
And you can't
stay mad at me.

751
00:37:16,599 --> 00:37:19,735
I'm sorry I raised
my voice back there, but...

752
00:37:19,803 --> 00:37:22,171
This trip is
more important to me

753
00:37:22,238 --> 00:37:24,874
Than I can truly
put into words.

754
00:37:24,942 --> 00:37:27,376
Do you understand?

755
00:37:30,648 --> 00:37:32,814
I'm getting hungry.

756
00:37:38,689 --> 00:37:41,423
Park the car.
I have an idea.

757
00:37:55,405 --> 00:37:57,707
Ok, what's
your big idea?

758
00:37:57,774 --> 00:37:59,441
I'll take your arm,

759
00:37:59,509 --> 00:38:02,745
And you tell them
I'm a blind
caricature artist.

760
00:38:02,813 --> 00:38:05,181
What?! No way.
That's crazy.

761
00:38:05,248 --> 00:38:07,483
You want
to eat tonight?

762
00:38:10,420 --> 00:38:12,588
Ok,
watch your step.

763
00:38:20,097 --> 00:38:23,265
Hi. Lovely day
for a fair, isn't it?

764
00:38:23,333 --> 00:38:25,267
Oh, it sure is, sir.

765
00:38:25,335 --> 00:38:28,037
Oh. She doesn't
see too well.

766
00:38:28,105 --> 00:38:31,140
Or... Really at all.

767
00:38:31,208 --> 00:38:32,742
Excuse me.

768
00:38:32,809 --> 00:38:34,076
Could I...

769
00:38:36,779 --> 00:38:37,980
Oh.

770
00:38:38,047 --> 00:38:40,048
From the contours
of your face,

771
00:38:40,117 --> 00:38:42,251
I'd say you were Irish.

772
00:38:42,319 --> 00:38:43,685
That's right.

773
00:38:43,753 --> 00:38:45,254
How do you do that?

774
00:38:45,322 --> 00:38:46,455
Ok, grandma.

775
00:38:46,523 --> 00:38:49,358
There's no entrance fee
for this,

776
00:38:49,426 --> 00:38:53,061
But we do request
a $5 donation, please.

777
00:38:53,130 --> 00:38:55,130
Oh, we're not here
to shop.

778
00:38:55,198 --> 00:38:57,232
I'm an artist.

779
00:38:59,369 --> 00:39:01,971
She does caricatures.

780
00:39:02,038 --> 00:39:04,006
But... But...

781
00:39:04,074 --> 00:39:05,741
She can't see.

782
00:39:05,776 --> 00:39:07,710
But that's
the beauty of it.

783
00:39:11,849 --> 00:39:14,583
[Overlapping chatter
and laughter]

784
00:39:33,303 --> 00:39:35,570
Here you are, son.
Thanks.

785
00:39:35,639 --> 00:39:36,839
Man: That's amazing.

786
00:39:36,907 --> 00:39:39,308
Oh, you don't know
the half of it.

787
00:39:40,877 --> 00:39:42,878
Thank you.

788
00:39:42,946 --> 00:39:45,247
How many is that?
16.

789
00:39:45,349 --> 00:39:47,383
Who's next?

790
00:40:08,038 --> 00:40:09,605
Ella bear...

791
00:40:09,673 --> 00:40:12,708
That voice of yours
is really something.

792
00:40:14,611 --> 00:40:16,412
That was the first time
I sang for anybody

793
00:40:16,479 --> 00:40:17,879
Besides my mom.

794
00:40:17,947 --> 00:40:20,649
Have you written
any songs for her?

795
00:40:20,717 --> 00:40:24,553
Actually, that's
what I'm working on
right now.

796
00:40:24,555 --> 00:40:25,921
Does it help?

797
00:40:27,991 --> 00:40:29,425
With what?

798
00:40:29,493 --> 00:40:32,594
Does it help you...
You know...

799
00:40:32,662 --> 00:40:35,731
When you're feeling
down about her?

800
00:40:35,799 --> 00:40:37,399
I don't know.

801
00:40:37,467 --> 00:40:39,334
You know what I do

802
00:40:39,403 --> 00:40:41,570
When I'm especially blue
about grandpa?

803
00:40:41,572 --> 00:40:43,706
I talk to him.

804
00:40:43,807 --> 00:40:45,107
Yeah, I--

805
00:40:45,175 --> 00:40:47,009
I heard you
in the car.

806
00:40:47,077 --> 00:40:49,244
I'm not embarrassed. I--

807
00:40:49,312 --> 00:40:52,448
Sometimes I talk
about normal stuff--

808
00:40:52,515 --> 00:40:54,283
My day...

809
00:40:54,350 --> 00:40:56,385
My feelings.

810
00:40:58,655 --> 00:41:00,756
Does it help?

811
00:41:00,824 --> 00:41:02,224
Sometimes.

812
00:41:03,827 --> 00:41:06,495
It makes me feel like
he's still with me.

813
00:41:14,137 --> 00:41:15,604
Richard: Yes,
I'm aware of the fact

814
00:41:15,672 --> 00:41:17,139
That they're not
technically missing.

815
00:41:17,207 --> 00:41:18,640
I have their
itinerary with me.

816
00:41:18,708 --> 00:41:20,342
<i>Man: Sir, they're</i>
<i>adults, not kids.</i>

817
00:41:20,410 --> 00:41:23,112
Yes, I'm aware of
the fact that they're
too old to be runaways.

818
00:41:23,179 --> 00:41:24,413
<i>Well, we don't</i>
<i>have the authority--</i>

819
00:41:24,480 --> 00:41:25,714
What do you
suggest we do?

820
00:41:25,782 --> 00:41:27,849
Wait until they break
the law or something?

821
00:41:27,918 --> 00:41:29,184
<i>Let's hope it doesn't</i>
<i>come to that.</i>

822
00:41:29,252 --> 00:41:31,320
Ok, thank you.
Thank you very much.

823
00:41:31,388 --> 00:41:33,688
Same to you. Good-bye.

824
00:41:37,761 --> 00:41:39,862
[Cell phone rings]

825
00:41:41,297 --> 00:41:43,165
Hey, Brenda.
What did you find out?

826
00:41:43,233 --> 00:41:45,534
<i>The card was last</i>
<i>used in Missouri.</i>
Missouri?!

827
00:41:45,602 --> 00:41:47,369
Did Mr. Nucci call
to harass me, too?

828
00:41:47,437 --> 00:41:49,705
Would you do me
a favor and get him
on the line, please?

829
00:41:49,772 --> 00:41:52,208
<i>Don't forget to eat.</i>
Thank you. What?

830
00:41:52,275 --> 00:41:53,476
<i>I said,</i>
<i>don't forget to eat.</i>

831
00:41:53,543 --> 00:41:55,877
Yes. Yes, I'll remember
to eat something.

832
00:41:55,945 --> 00:41:57,413
<i>Ok.</i>
Ok.

833
00:41:57,481 --> 00:41:59,482
<i>Ok. 'Cause you</i>
<i>know what, sweetheart?</i>

834
00:41:59,549 --> 00:42:01,116
<i>You are like a toothpick.</i>
<i>I mean, personally,</i>

835
00:42:01,184 --> 00:42:03,319
<i>I like a man with</i>
<i>a little more meat</i>
<i>on his bones.</i>

836
00:42:03,387 --> 00:42:04,486
Annie:
Did you know,

837
00:42:04,554 --> 00:42:06,188
After all those years
of painting,

838
00:42:06,256 --> 00:42:09,592
Today was the first time
I've ever actually
sold something?

839
00:42:09,660 --> 00:42:11,127
Really?

840
00:42:12,528 --> 00:42:14,096
I think we've done
quite a bit of living

841
00:42:14,163 --> 00:42:15,998
In the last
couple of days.

842
00:42:16,065 --> 00:42:19,135
How are you feeling?

843
00:42:19,136 --> 00:42:20,602
I'm feeling
the same as I was

844
00:42:20,670 --> 00:42:23,172
When you asked me
ten minutes ago.

845
00:42:23,239 --> 00:42:25,007
That's why
I have these.

846
00:42:28,745 --> 00:42:31,714
How did you know
grandpa was the one?

847
00:42:33,951 --> 00:42:35,818
He touched my hand.

848
00:42:36,153 --> 00:42:37,185
And?

849
00:42:37,321 --> 00:42:38,987
Ella bear...

850
00:42:39,055 --> 00:42:42,058
When your grandpa
touched my hand
for the first time,

851
00:42:42,125 --> 00:42:44,060
I had to
actually look down

852
00:42:44,094 --> 00:42:45,427
To see if it was
still there.

853
00:42:45,529 --> 00:42:48,196
I knew right then.

854
00:42:48,264 --> 00:42:50,232
That's it?

855
00:42:50,300 --> 00:42:54,269
That sounds like
something out of
a cheesy romance novel.

856
00:42:54,337 --> 00:42:56,438
I know it sounds silly.

857
00:42:56,540 --> 00:42:58,273
Someday you'll know
what I mean.

858
00:43:02,145 --> 00:43:04,079
So, tell me
about your brother.

859
00:43:04,147 --> 00:43:05,915
How did we
get to that?

860
00:43:05,982 --> 00:43:07,750
I don't know.
I mean...

861
00:43:07,817 --> 00:43:10,285
These are all
the things that
I don't know about you.

862
00:43:10,387 --> 00:43:12,921
There isn't
much to tell.

863
00:43:12,989 --> 00:43:15,457
Ok, I sang
at that truck stop,

864
00:43:15,525 --> 00:43:17,826
And I showed you
my notebook.

865
00:43:17,861 --> 00:43:19,895
Now it's time for you
to do something that
you don't want to do.

866
00:43:19,963 --> 00:43:22,631
Well...

867
00:43:22,699 --> 00:43:25,701
Doug is almost 20 years
younger than I am,

868
00:43:25,768 --> 00:43:27,737
And he lives
in California.

869
00:43:27,804 --> 00:43:29,338
Why don't you
talk to him?

870
00:43:29,406 --> 00:43:31,173
It's a long story.

871
00:43:31,240 --> 00:43:34,443
I wanted to teach him
a lesson years ago.

872
00:43:34,511 --> 00:43:37,780
I think he got the lesson,
but he never forgave me.

873
00:43:40,116 --> 00:43:42,451
Have you ever been
skinny-dipping?

874
00:43:42,518 --> 00:43:43,819
No.

875
00:43:43,887 --> 00:43:45,220
I keep thinking about
that pool

876
00:43:45,288 --> 00:43:49,291
By that big country club
when we were driving in here.

877
00:43:49,359 --> 00:43:51,894
Why don't we chalk up
another first while
we're on the road?

878
00:43:51,995 --> 00:43:53,762
What do you say?

879
00:43:53,864 --> 00:43:55,097
No.
Why not?

880
00:43:55,165 --> 00:43:59,602
Because you're sick,
and, no offense,

881
00:43:59,669 --> 00:44:03,005
But the idea
of skinny-dipping
with my grandma

882
00:44:03,073 --> 00:44:05,875
Doesn't sound like
a whole lot of fun.

883
00:44:05,942 --> 00:44:08,244
It actually sounds
kind of creepy.

884
00:44:08,311 --> 00:44:10,446
Well, I'm going
skinny-dipping.

885
00:44:23,960 --> 00:44:25,661
Are you sure
you want to do this?

886
00:44:25,728 --> 00:44:27,763
You only live once.

887
00:44:34,671 --> 00:44:37,038
I don't know if I can
make it over the fence.

888
00:44:40,042 --> 00:44:41,810
How did you
get over there?

889
00:44:41,845 --> 00:44:43,478
The gate's open.

890
00:44:46,115 --> 00:44:47,716
That works.

891
00:44:49,385 --> 00:44:51,119
Ella:
How's the temperature?

892
00:44:51,187 --> 00:44:52,754
Annie: Who cares?

893
00:45:01,064 --> 00:45:04,867
Oh, it's beautiful
in here!

894
00:45:04,935 --> 00:45:06,302
You didn't
finish your story.

895
00:45:06,369 --> 00:45:07,669
Tell me about
your brother.

896
00:45:07,737 --> 00:45:10,806
Doug was living with us

897
00:45:10,874 --> 00:45:13,075
After my folks passed.

898
00:45:13,176 --> 00:45:17,245
He didn't deal with
their passing all that well.

899
00:45:17,280 --> 00:45:20,849
He was good kid,
but for a while there,

900
00:45:20,851 --> 00:45:24,019
He always seemed
to find trouble.

901
00:45:24,087 --> 00:45:26,121
One night he got
caught shoplifting,

902
00:45:26,189 --> 00:45:28,023
And they arrested him.

903
00:45:28,091 --> 00:45:30,425
I thought he should spend
one night in jail

904
00:45:30,493 --> 00:45:32,227
Before we got him out.

905
00:45:32,295 --> 00:45:34,963
Like I said,
to teach him a lesson.

906
00:45:35,031 --> 00:45:36,298
When we finally
got him out,

907
00:45:36,366 --> 00:45:38,700
He was awfully
mad at me.

908
00:45:38,802 --> 00:45:41,403
We got into
a huge fight,

909
00:45:41,470 --> 00:45:45,574
Said things I'm sure
we both regretted
our whole lives.

910
00:45:45,609 --> 00:45:48,010
Then he packed
his bags,

911
00:45:48,077 --> 00:45:49,511
Moved to California,

912
00:45:49,579 --> 00:45:51,046
And I never heard
from him again.

913
00:45:51,113 --> 00:45:53,214
Ella: What happened
to him?

914
00:45:53,282 --> 00:45:55,617
Like I said,
he was a good kid.

915
00:45:55,685 --> 00:46:00,889
He learned his lesson
and just... Lived his life.

916
00:46:00,957 --> 00:46:02,791
Why don't we stop
and see him?

917
00:46:02,859 --> 00:46:04,659
Doug?

918
00:46:04,727 --> 00:46:06,862
I wouldn't know
what to say.

919
00:46:06,929 --> 00:46:10,331
[Police siren whooping]

920
00:46:10,333 --> 00:46:12,634
Oh, poo!

921
00:46:12,702 --> 00:46:14,135
Man: Yes, officer.

922
00:46:14,204 --> 00:46:16,371
We are always having
trespassers.

923
00:46:16,439 --> 00:46:18,440
This is not a public pool,
you understand.

924
00:46:18,508 --> 00:46:21,677
I understand, sir.
I'll take care of it.

925
00:46:21,678 --> 00:46:23,512
I thank you.
Mm-hmm.

926
00:46:25,248 --> 00:46:27,982
Uh, well, um...

927
00:46:28,050 --> 00:46:31,986
That gentleman there--
that's Mr. Langelos.

928
00:46:31,988 --> 00:46:34,089
Annie: Does he live
at the country club?

929
00:46:34,157 --> 00:46:36,926
Uh, heh. Ma'am...
This isn't a country club.

930
00:46:36,993 --> 00:46:38,860
It's his private
residence.

931
00:46:38,895 --> 00:46:41,964
Oh, my.

932
00:46:42,031 --> 00:46:44,466
My partner here will
drive your car behind me,

933
00:46:44,534 --> 00:46:46,535
Save you a $100
impound fee.

934
00:46:46,603 --> 00:46:49,438
Thank you.
Sure.

935
00:46:53,709 --> 00:46:55,177
Officer: Just, uh,
come this way.

936
00:46:55,245 --> 00:46:56,411
Thank you.

937
00:46:58,981 --> 00:47:00,582
[Grunts]

938
00:47:00,650 --> 00:47:02,317
Ok.

939
00:47:03,887 --> 00:47:05,587
[Kiss]

940
00:47:25,909 --> 00:47:27,475
Turn the other way.

941
00:47:30,280 --> 00:47:32,181
Annie: One day we'll
look back on this

942
00:47:32,248 --> 00:47:34,482
As our
"night in jail".

943
00:47:34,550 --> 00:47:35,951
[Chuckles]

944
00:47:36,019 --> 00:47:38,420
Boy, Doug would
find this a real hoot.

945
00:47:38,487 --> 00:47:40,755
His goodie-goodie
sister in the can.

946
00:47:40,824 --> 00:47:42,324
Grandma,
this isn't funny!

947
00:47:42,391 --> 00:47:44,592
God, don't you take
anything seriously?

948
00:47:44,661 --> 00:47:45,794
Oh, we'll be
out of here in no time.

949
00:47:45,862 --> 00:47:48,330
We don't have money
for the fine.

950
00:47:48,331 --> 00:47:49,598
We're gonna have to
call dad.

951
00:47:49,666 --> 00:47:51,333
I'm sure he'll be
joining us

952
00:47:51,401 --> 00:47:53,669
Sooner rather
than later.

953
00:47:57,239 --> 00:48:00,842
Uh, you sure there isn't
anyone you'd like to call?

954
00:48:00,910 --> 00:48:02,977
Uh, in a moment, son.

955
00:48:03,045 --> 00:48:06,114
Right now...
Would you mind

956
00:48:06,182 --> 00:48:08,550
Pointing me to that
bathroom over there?

957
00:48:08,618 --> 00:48:11,186
Uh... Well,
miss Eason, um--

958
00:48:11,254 --> 00:48:12,988
Oh, call me Annie.

959
00:48:13,056 --> 00:48:16,558
Annie. That's really just
for police personnel only.

960
00:48:16,625 --> 00:48:21,730
Now, you wouldn't want
your mother using that,
would you?

961
00:48:23,266 --> 00:48:24,900
Uh, no, ma'am.

962
00:48:24,968 --> 00:48:28,336
Could you find it
in your heart to...

963
00:48:28,404 --> 00:48:32,007
Treat me like
your mother?
Just this time?

964
00:48:33,877 --> 00:48:35,310
Uh...

965
00:48:37,180 --> 00:48:38,547
What the heck.

966
00:48:41,117 --> 00:48:42,951
[Door opens]

967
00:48:43,053 --> 00:48:44,386
This way.

968
00:48:44,453 --> 00:48:46,054
Where's your partner?

969
00:48:46,122 --> 00:48:47,756
Oh, he's out
on a call.

970
00:48:49,259 --> 00:48:50,825
Would you be a dear...

971
00:48:50,894 --> 00:48:52,727
And make sure
it's clean?

972
00:48:52,795 --> 00:48:54,229
I have a thing
about bathrooms.

973
00:48:54,297 --> 00:48:55,530
Sure.

974
00:48:57,167 --> 00:48:59,168
Yep, looks ok
to me, Annie.

975
00:48:59,235 --> 00:49:00,602
Annie?

976
00:49:00,670 --> 00:49:02,404
Let's go.
Annie?

977
00:49:02,472 --> 00:49:04,306
No!
Ella Mildred Eason...

978
00:49:04,374 --> 00:49:05,640
It's now or never.

979
00:49:08,311 --> 00:49:10,379
[Tires screech]

980
00:49:16,920 --> 00:49:20,522
Cross another one
off life's to-do list.

981
00:49:20,589 --> 00:49:23,025
We're a regular
Thelma and Louise.

982
00:49:23,092 --> 00:49:24,293
We're gonna
go to jail.

983
00:49:24,360 --> 00:49:25,861
We've already
been to jail.

984
00:49:25,962 --> 00:49:27,396
No, I mean,
<i>real</i> jail,

985
00:49:27,463 --> 00:49:29,064
Where there's gangs
and murderers.

986
00:49:29,132 --> 00:49:30,299
Don't be silly.

987
00:49:30,366 --> 00:49:31,666
We're gonna get
caught, grandma.

988
00:49:31,734 --> 00:49:33,135
Relax, Ella bear.

989
00:49:33,202 --> 00:49:34,702
Relax?

990
00:49:34,770 --> 00:49:37,272
How am I supposed
to relax?

991
00:49:37,374 --> 00:49:40,142
You guilted me into
going on this trip
with you.

992
00:49:40,209 --> 00:49:42,110
You--you lied
and told me

993
00:49:42,178 --> 00:49:43,945
You need some kind
of heart surgery.

994
00:49:44,013 --> 00:49:46,214
And then you broke us
out of jail.

995
00:49:46,282 --> 00:49:48,616
You don't need me on
this trip with you.

996
00:49:48,651 --> 00:49:49,818
You just need
a chauffeur.

997
00:49:49,886 --> 00:49:51,787
That's not true.
Oh, yeah?

998
00:49:51,855 --> 00:49:53,288
Well, that's how
I see it.

999
00:49:53,356 --> 00:49:55,690
You're going through
a very hard time,

1000
00:49:55,758 --> 00:49:58,059
And it's hard to see
the light at the end
of the tunnel.

1001
00:49:58,128 --> 00:50:01,330
But trust me.
Trust yourself.
It will be there.

1002
00:50:01,397 --> 00:50:02,897
And as far as needing
a chauffeur,

1003
00:50:02,965 --> 00:50:06,135
I don't need a chauffeur.
I need a best friend.

1004
00:50:06,202 --> 00:50:09,505
And she happens to be
sitting right here
next to me.

1005
00:50:09,572 --> 00:50:11,640
Oh, come here.

1006
00:50:16,446 --> 00:50:18,646
Now, tell me
that didn't feel good.

1007
00:50:18,748 --> 00:50:20,349
That didn't feel good.

1008
00:50:22,218 --> 00:50:24,486
Ok, it felt
kind of good.

1009
00:50:24,487 --> 00:50:26,154
[Laughs] oh...

1010
00:50:26,221 --> 00:50:27,789
Just make that
the last thing

1011
00:50:27,857 --> 00:50:29,658
We cross
off the list.

1012
00:50:29,726 --> 00:50:31,826
Deal.

1013
00:50:31,894 --> 00:50:34,329
[Police sirens blaring]

1014
00:50:34,397 --> 00:50:36,431
Ohh.

1015
00:50:42,071 --> 00:50:43,839
I drove just about
all night.

1016
00:50:43,907 --> 00:50:45,206
